[{'node': {'text': 'i. destructive conformity
-
‚ÄúWe treat woman like pieces of meat.
As if the only power they have is through their body. 
The moment you comprehend people are more than physical, 
the more beautiful the entirely of a person becomes.

We get our images of women through the media.
This gives us a warped view of beauty and 
what a body is meant to look like. 
As if there is such thing as a right body, a normal body, a perfect body.

Conforming to these ideas is destructive 
We cut away at self-worth until there‚Äôs nothing left 
but the molded person you confined into being. 
Not even realizing you‚Äôre meant to be so much more.

We compare ourselves to these false goddesses, manipulated and altered.
As if they‚Äôll teach us how not to need.
As if they‚Äôll teach us how to be loved.
Be your own goddess, find beauty in yourself before others.‚Äù
-
continuation of a work I did years ago. it links to this amateur prose I wrote. I‚Äôve always wanted to explore it further and finally forced myself today. my true vision for these pieces are in color, on canvas. but these will be my inspiration until I‚Äôm ready to materialize it.'}}]

[{'node': {'text': "Had the pleasure of designing and tattooing a #trashpolkatattoo .
.
.
The client wanted a compass tattoo, I asked if he would like anything to go with it, he wasn't sure he said, so I asked him what his thoughts were on brush strokes, he didn't dislike them he said common ground, leave it to me I said. That was pretty much how it went down. Jokes aside though, I don't get people that see a tattoo and want the exact same one, where's your sense of creativity that's what the tattoo artist is there for. It's cool if you found a tattoo you like and show it to your tattoo artist to get him on the right track, but if you straight up copy someone's tattoo that's just lame you aren't showing who you are, you are just showing what or who you like to copy.
.
.
.
